{"title_page": "World Malaria Day", "text_new": "{{Infobox holiday\n|holiday_name  = World Malaria Day\n|type          = international\n|longtype      = \n|image         = World Health Organization Flag.jpg\n|caption       = \n|official_name = \n|nickname      = \n|observedby    = All Member States of the [[World Health Organization]]\n|duration      = 1 day\n|frequency     = annual\n|scheduling    = same day each year\n|date          = April 25\n|celebrations  = \n|relatedto     = \n}}\n\n'''World Malaria Day''' ('''WMD''') is an [[international observance]] commemorated every year on 25 April and recognizes global efforts to control [[malaria]]. Globally, 3.3 billion people in 106 countries are at risk of malaria.<ref name=WHO2010>World Health Organization,[http://www.who.int/malaria/world_malaria_report_2010/en/index.html ''World Malaria Report 2010''.]</ref> In 2012, malaria caused an estimated 627,000 deaths, mostly among African children.<ref>World Health Organization, [http://www.who.int/mediacentre/factsheets/fs094/en/ Malaria.] WHO Fact sheet N\u00b094, updated March 2014. Accessed 8 April 2014.</ref> Asia, Latin America, and to a lesser extent the Middle East and parts of Europe are also affected.\n\nWorld Malaria Day sprung out of the efforts taking place across the African continent to commemorate '''Africa Malaria Day'''. WMD is one of eight official [[global health|global public health]] campaigns currently marked by the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO), along with [[World Health Day]], [[World Blood Donor Day]], [[World Immunization Week]], [[World Tuberculosis Day]], [[World No Tobacco Day]], [[World Hepatitis Day]] and [[World AIDS Day]].<ref>World Health Organization, [http://www.who.int/campaigns/en WHO campaigns.]</ref>\n\nAccording to the most recent World Malaria Report, the global tally of malaria reached 429,000 malaria deaths and 212 million new cases in 2015. The rate of new malaria cases fell by 21 per cent globally between 2010 and 2015, and malaria death rates fell by 29 per cent in the same period. In sub-Saharan Africa, case incidence and death rates fell by 21 per cent and 31 per cent, respectively.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Jatinder|first1=Kaur|title=World Malaria Day Asks Malaria Prevention|url=http://abclive.in/world-malaria-day-malaria-prevention/|accessdate=30 April 2017|agency=ABC Live|issue=Online|publisher=ABC Live}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n'''World Malaria Day''' was established in May 2007 by the 60th session of the [[World Health Assembly]], WHO's decision-making body. The day was established to provide \"education and understanding of malaria\" and spread information on \"year-long intensified implementation of national malaria-control strategies, including community-based activities for malaria prevention and treatment in endemic areas.\"<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20070619005021/http://www.who.int/gb/ebwha/pdf_files/WHA60/A60_R18-en.pdf Malaria, including proposal for establishment of World Malaria Day (WHA Resolution 60.18)]</ref>\n\nPrior to the establishment of WMD, '''Africa Malaria Day'''<ref>[http://www.rollbackmalaria.org/globaladvocacy/africamalariaday.html Africa Malaria Days 2001-2007]</ref> was held on April 25. Africa Malaria Day began in 2001, one year after the historic ''Abuja Declaration''<ref>African Summit on Roll Back Malaria, [http://www.rollbackmalaria.org/docs/abuja_declaration_final.htm Abuja Declaration.] Abuja, 25 April 2000.</ref> was signed by 44 malaria-endemic countries at the African Summit on Malaria.<ref>[http://www.rollbackmalaria.org/globaladvocacy/africansummit2000.html African Malaria Summit]</ref>\n\nWorld Malaria Day allows for corporations (such as [[ExxonMobil]]<ref>ExxonMobil, [http://www.exxonmobil.com/Corporate/community_malaria_wmd.aspx Commemorating World Malaria Day 2013.]</ref>), multinational organizations (such as [[Malaria No More]]<ref>Malaria No More UK, [http://malarianomore.org.uk/world-malaria-day World Malaria Day.]</ref>) and grassroots organizations (such as [[Mosquitoes Suck Tour]]<ref>http://dontbiteme.ca/more-about-malaria/</ref>) globally to work together to bring [[awareness]] to malaria and advocate for [[health policy|policy]] changes.<ref>Malaria Community, [http://www.worldmalariaday.org/about_the_site_en.cfm World Malaria Day.]</ref>\n\n==Themes==\nEach World Malaria Day focuses on a specific theme. Current and past themes include the following:\n*World Malaria Day 2020: \"Zero malaria starts with me\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wplinequotes.xyz/2020/04/world-malaria-day-quotes-slogan-theme-history-facts-poster-images-pictures.html|title=World Malaria Day 2020: Zero malaria starts with me|website=WpLINEQuotes|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref>\n*World Malaria Day 2019: \"Zero malaria starts with me\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.who.int/campaigns/world-malaria-day/world-malaria-day-2019|title=World Malaria Day 2019: Zero malaria starts with me|website=WHO|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-04-02}}</ref>\n*World Malaria Day 2018: \"Ready to beat malaria\"\n*World Malaria Day 2017: \"LETS Close The Gap\"\n*World Malaria Day 2016: \"End Malaria For Good\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://globalhealthstrategies.com/blog/impact/world-malaria-day-2017/|title=World Malaria Day 2017 - Global Health Strategies|work=Global Health Strategies|access-date=2018-01-13|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.afro.who.int/media-centre/events/world-malaria-day-2017-end-malaria-good|title=World Malaria Day 2017: End malaria for good|website=WHO {{!}} Regional Office for Africa|language=en|access-date=2018-01-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.who.int/campaigns/malaria-day/2016/event/en/|title=World Malaria Day 2016: End malaria for good|website=World Health Organization|language=en-GB|access-date=2018-01-13}}</ref>\n*World Malaria Day 2013-2014-2015: \"Invest in the future: defeat malaria\"<ref>[http://www.rollbackmalaria.org/worldmalariaday/index.html World Malaria Day 2013-2015 web site]</ref>\n*World Malaria Day 2012: \"Sustain Gains, Save Lives: Invest in Malaria\"<ref>[http://www.rollbackmalaria.org/worldmalariaday20412/index.html World Malaria Day 2012 web site]</ref>\n*World Malaria Day 2011: \"Achieving Progress and Impact\"<ref>[http://www.rollbackmalaria.org/worldmalariaday20011/index.html World Malaria Day 2011 web site]</ref>\n*World Malaria Day 2009-2010: \"Counting malaria out\"<ref>[http://www.rollbackmalaria.org/worldmalariaday2010/index.html World Malaria Day 2009-2010 web site]</ref>\n*World Malaria Day 2008: \"Malaria: a disease without borders\"<ref>[http://www.rollbackmalaria.org/worldmalariaday2008/index.html World Malaria Day 2008 web site]</ref>\n\n==Global Events==\n===Europe===\nLeading to World Malaria Day 2014, the European Vaccine Initiative announced sixteen new projects for the acceleration of malaria vaccine development.<ref>European Vaccine Initiative. [https://web.archive.org/web/20141011170830/http://www.euvaccine.eu/sites/default/files/uploads/docs/news/EVI_WMD-PR_final_140415.pdf World Malaria Day 2014: New vaccine candidates against malaria enter clinical development.] 22 April 2014. Accessed 7 October 2014.</ref> The projects were to be undertaken by an international consortium involving partners from the public and private sectors from Europe, USA and Africa.\n\n===India===\nFor World Malaria Day 2017, efforts across India included a series of measures to control the spread of this vector-borne disease. The coastal city of Mangaluru identified open water resources to target for eliminating mosquitos that spread malaria.<ref>Times of India, [http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/mangaluru/world-malaria-day-statistics-indicate-dip-in-mangaluru-cases/articleshow/58363738.cms \"World Malaria Day: Statistics indicate dip in Mangaluru cases,\"] Apr 25, 2017 (accessed Apr 25, 2017).</ref>\n\n===Nigeria===\n[[File:Mosquito Netting.jpg|thumb|Ceiling hung mosquito netting.]]\nEvents marking World Malaria Day 2014 in Nigeria included a demonstration of [[anti-malarial bed net]]s, testing and distribution of anti-malarial drugs, seminars on progress in combating and controlling malaria, and the inclusion of African footballers in the campaign to combat malaria.<ref>Federal Ministry of Health. [http://www.nmcp.gov.ng/World-Malaria-Day-2014 Are You Ready for World Malaria Day 2014?] Abuja, 11 April 2014. Accessed 7 October 2014.</ref>\n\nAs of 2016, the Federal Ministry of Health has pledged to end Malaria.<ref>[http://www.nmcp.gov.ng/ \"Home\"]</ref> The U.S. Ambassador to Nigeria, James F. Entwistle, has pledged continued support and noted the possibility of ending Malaria in Nigeria.<ref>[https://nigeria.usembassy.gov/oped_04252016.html \"Opinion Editorial\"]</ref>\n\n===United States===\n[[Image:George W. Bush delivers remarks on Malaria Awareness Day 2007.jpg|thumb|President Bush addresses Americans in The White House Rose Garden about the issues of malaria]]\nApril 25 was designated as ''Malaria Awareness Day'' in 2007 by President [[George W. Bush]], who called on Americans to join in on the goal to eradicate malaria on the African continent.<ref name=\"GB\">George W. Bush. The White House: Office of the Press Secretary. [https://georgewbush-whitehouse.archives.gov/news/releases/2007/04/20070424-11.html Malaria Awareness Day, 2007.] 24 April 2007.</ref>  President Bush described it as a day when \"we focus our attention on all who suffer from this terrible disease -- especially the millions on the continent of Africa. We remember the millions more who died from this entirely preventable and treatable disease.\"  President Bush shared the White House's strategic plan against malaria, which included endeavors to distribute bed nets with the New York-based nonprofit group [[Malaria No More]].<ref name=\"WH\">The White House: Office of the Press Secretary. [https://georgewbush-whitehouse.archives.gov/news/releases/2007/04/20070425-2.html President Bush and Mrs. Bush Discuss Malaria Awareness Day.] 25 April 2007.</ref>\n\nOther former U.S. Presidents are involved in anti-malaria efforts. Former President [[Bill Clinton]]'s [[Clinton Foundation]] includes an anti-malaria component that, according to director [[Inder Singh (philanthropist)|Inder Singh]] has distributed anti-malaria drugs to millions in Africa and Asia.<ref name=\"MIT\">[http://hst.mit.edu/servlet/ControllerServlet?handler=PublicHandler&action=browse&pageId=2261 BEP grad Inder Singh orchestrates affordable malaria drug development], Harvard-MIT Health Sciences.</ref>\n\nMany prominent companies, organizations, and celebrities have declared initiatives to join the fight against malaria to mark this day. These include a $3 million \"challenge grant\" announced by [[ExxonMobil]] to match donations dollar by dollar to [[Malaria No More]], as part of the \"[[Idol Gives Back]]\" episodes of [[American Idol]], which was aired on Malaria Awareness Day.  [[Major League Soccer]] Commissioner [[Don Garber]] also announced that the league would promote malaria awareness and bed net fundraising promotions in the month of April leading up to  Malaria Awareness Day. Actress [[Ashley Judd]], announced the April launch of a new initiative called \u201c5 & Alive,\u201d which will focus on the devastating effects of malaria on children under 5.  The [[Boys & Girls Clubs of America]] announced their own national campaign called \"Malaria Prevention: Deadly Disease.  Simple Solution\", which will partner with Malaria No More to approach all 4.7 Million Club members worldwide to ask for $10 bed net donations.<ref name=\"MNM\">Malaria No More. [https://web.archive.org/web/20070928013156/http://www.malarianomore.org/media/malarianomore-mad-32907.pdf Run up to April 25, the First Malaria Awareness Day in the US.] 29 March 2007.</ref>\n\nThe movement is not without its critics, such as the African economist [[Dambisa Moyo]] who warns that the short term benefits of aid such as mosquito nets can have long term detrimental effects to the sustainability of African economies. When the markets are flooded with foreign nets then this puts African entrepreneurs out of business.{{citation needed|date=October 2014}}\n\n==See also==\n*[https://www.festivaldayes.com/%e0%a4%b5%e0%a4%b0%e0%a5%8d%e0%a4%b2%e0%a5%8d%e0%a4%a1-%e0%a4%ae%e0%a4%b2%e0%a5%87%e0%a4%b0%e0%a4%bf%e0%a4%af%e0%a4%be-%e0%a4%a6%e0%a4%bf%e0%a4%b5%e0%a4%b8/ World Malaria Day 2020]\n*[[Global Malaria Action Plan]]\n*[[Malaria Day in the Americas]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.worldmalariaday.org World Malaria Day website]\n*[http://www.rollbackmalaria.org/worldmalariaday/ Roll Back Malaria Partnership - World Malaria Day]\n*[http://www.malaria.com/news/world-malaria-day-2015 MALARIA.com - World Malaria Day]\n*[http://www.who.int/malaria/en/ WHO Global Malaria Programme]\n*[https://georgewbush-whitehouse.archives.gov/news/releases/2007/04/20070424-11.html Malaria Awareness Day, 2007 Proclamation by U.S. President George W. Bush]\n\n{{malaria}}\n\n[[Category:Malaria]]\n[[Category:Health awareness days]]\n[[Category:International observances]]\n[[Category:United Nations days]]\n[[Category:April observances]]\n[[Category:World Health Organization]]\n\n[[fr:Journ\u00e9e mondiale du paludisme]]\n[[ru:\u0412\u0441\u0435\u043c\u0438\u0440\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0434\u0435\u043d\u044c \u0431\u043e\u0440\u044c\u0431\u044b \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0442\u0438\u0432 \u043c\u0430\u043b\u044f\u0440\u0438\u0438]]\n[[zh:\u4e16\u754c\u759f\u75be\u65e5]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox holiday\n|holiday_name  = World Malaria Day\n|type          = international\n|longtype      = \n|image         = World Health Organization Flag.jpg\n|caption       = \n|official_name = \n|nickname      = \n|observedby    = All Member States of the [[World Health Organization]]\n|duration      = 1 day\n|frequency     = annual\n|scheduling    = same day each year\n|date          = April 25\n|celebrations  = \n|relatedto     = \n}}\n\n'''World Malaria Day''' ('''WMD''') is an [[international observance]] commemorated every year on 25 April and recognizes global efforts to control [[malaria]]. Globally, 3.3 billion people in 106 countries are at risk of malaria.<ref name=WHO2010>World Health Organization,[http://www.who.int/malaria/world_malaria_report_2010/en/index.html ''World Malaria Report 2010''.]</ref> In 2012, malaria caused an estimated 627,000 deaths, mostly among African children.<ref>World Health Organization, [http://www.who.int/mediacentre/factsheets/fs094/en/ Malaria.] WHO Fact sheet N\u00b094, updated March 2014. Accessed 8 April 2014.</ref> Asia, Latin America, and to a lesser extent the Middle East and parts of Europe are also affected.\n\nWorld Malaria Day sprung out of the efforts taking place across the African continent to commemorate '''Africa Malaria Day'''. WMD is one of eight official [[global health|global public health]] campaigns currently marked by the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO), along with [[World Health Day]], [[World Blood Donor Day]], [[World Immunization Week]], [[World Tuberculosis Day]], [[World No Tobacco Day]], [[World Hepatitis Day]] and [[World AIDS Day]].<ref>World Health Organization, [http://www.who.int/campaigns/en WHO campaigns.]</ref>\n\nAccording to the most recent World Malaria Report, the global tally of malaria reached 429,000 malaria deaths and 212 million new cases in 2015. The rate of new malaria cases fell by 21 per cent globally between 2010 and 2015, and malaria death rates fell by 29 per cent in the same period. In sub-Saharan Africa, case incidence and death rates fell by 21 per cent and 31 per cent, respectively.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Jatinder|first1=Kaur|title=World Malaria Day Asks Malaria Prevention|url=http://abclive.in/world-malaria-day-malaria-prevention/|accessdate=30 April 2017|agency=ABC Live|issue=Online|publisher=ABC Live}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n'''World Malaria Day''' was established in May 2007 by the 60th session of the [[World Health Assembly]], WHO's decision-making body. The day was established to provide \"education and understanding of malaria\" and spread information on \"year-long intensified implementation of national malaria-control strategies, including community-based activities for malaria prevention and treatment in endemic areas.\"<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20070619005021/http://www.who.int/gb/ebwha/pdf_files/WHA60/A60_R18-en.pdf Malaria, including proposal for establishment of World Malaria Day (WHA Resolution 60.18)]</ref>\n\nPrior to the establishment of WMD, '''Africa Malaria Day'''<ref>[http://www.rollbackmalaria.org/globaladvocacy/africamalariaday.html Africa Malaria Days 2001-2007]</ref> was held on April 25. Africa Malaria Day began in 2001, one year after the historic ''Abuja Declaration''<ref>African Summit on Roll Back Malaria, [http://www.rollbackmalaria.org/docs/abuja_declaration_final.htm Abuja Declaration.] Abuja, 25 April 2000.</ref> was signed by 44 malaria-endemic countries at the African Summit on Malaria.<ref>[http://www.rollbackmalaria.org/globaladvocacy/africansummit2000.html African Malaria Summit]</ref>\n\nWorld Malaria Day allows for corporations (such as [[ExxonMobil]]<ref>ExxonMobil, [http://www.exxonmobil.com/Corporate/community_malaria_wmd.aspx Commemorating World Malaria Day 2013.]</ref>), multinational organizations (such as [[Malaria No More]]<ref>Malaria No More UK, [http://malarianomore.org.uk/world-malaria-day World Malaria Day.]</ref>) and grassroots organizations (such as [[Mosquitoes Suck Tour]]<ref>http://dontbiteme.ca/more-about-malaria/</ref>) globally to work together to bring [[awareness]] to malaria and advocate for [[health policy|policy]] changes.<ref>Malaria Community, [http://www.worldmalariaday.org/about_the_site_en.cfm World Malaria Day.]</ref>\n\n==Themes==\nEach World Malaria Day focuses on a specific theme. Current and past themes include the following:\n*World Malaria Day 2020: \"Zero malaria starts with me\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wplinequotes.xyz/2020/04/world-malaria-day-quotes-slogan-theme-history-facts-poster-images-pictures.html|title=World Malaria Day 2020: Zero malaria starts with me|website=WpLINEQuotes|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref>\n*World Malaria Day 2019: \"Zero malaria starts with me\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.who.int/campaigns/world-malaria-day/world-malaria-day-2019|title=World Malaria Day 2019: Zero malaria starts with me|website=WHO|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-04-02}}</ref>\n*World Malaria Day 2018: \"Ready to beat malaria\"\n*World Malaria Day 2017: \"LETS Close The Gap\"\n*World Malaria Day 2016: \"End Malaria For Good\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://globalhealthstrategies.com/blog/impact/world-malaria-day-2017/|title=World Malaria Day 2017 - Global Health Strategies|work=Global Health Strategies|access-date=2018-01-13|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.afro.who.int/media-centre/events/world-malaria-day-2017-end-malaria-good|title=World Malaria Day 2017: End malaria for good|website=WHO {{!}} Regional Office for Africa|language=en|access-date=2018-01-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.who.int/campaigns/malaria-day/2016/event/en/|title=World Malaria Day 2016: End malaria for good|website=World Health Organization|language=en-GB|access-date=2018-01-13}}</ref>\n*World Malaria Day 2013-2014-2015: \"Invest in the future: defeat malaria\"<ref>[http://www.rollbackmalaria.org/worldmalariaday/index.html World Malaria Day 2013-2015 web site]</ref>\n*World Malaria Day 2012: \"Sustain Gains, Save Lives: Invest in Malaria\"<ref>[http://www.rollbackmalaria.org/worldmalariaday20412/index.html World Malaria Day 2012 web site]</ref>\n*World Malaria Day 2011: \"Achieving Progress and Impact\"<ref>[http://www.rollbackmalaria.org/worldmalariaday20011/index.html World Malaria Day 2011 web site]</ref>\n*World Malaria Day 2009-2010: \"Counting malaria out\"<ref>[http://www.rollbackmalaria.org/worldmalariaday2010/index.html World Malaria Day 2009-2010 web site]</ref>\n*World Malaria Day 2008: \"Malaria: a disease without borders\"<ref>[http://www.rollbackmalaria.org/worldmalariaday2008/index.html World Malaria Day 2008 web site]</ref>\n\n==Global Events==\n===Europe===\nLeading to World Malaria Day 2014, the European Vaccine Initiative announced sixteen new projects for the acceleration of malaria vaccine development.<ref>European Vaccine Initiative. [https://web.archive.org/web/20141011170830/http://www.euvaccine.eu/sites/default/files/uploads/docs/news/EVI_WMD-PR_final_140415.pdf World Malaria Day 2014: New vaccine candidates against malaria enter clinical development.] 22 April 2014. Accessed 7 October 2014.</ref> The projects were to be undertaken by an international consortium involving partners from the public and private sectors from Europe, USA and Africa.\n\n===India===\nFor World Malaria Day 2017, efforts across India included a series of measures to control the spread of this vector-borne disease. The coastal city of Mangaluru identified open water resources to target for eliminating mosquitos that spread malaria.<ref>Times of India, [http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/mangaluru/world-malaria-day-statistics-indicate-dip-in-mangaluru-cases/articleshow/58363738.cms \"World Malaria Day: Statistics indicate dip in Mangaluru cases,\"] Apr 25, 2017 (accessed Apr 25, 2017).</ref>\n\n===Nigeria===\n[[File:Mosquito Netting.jpg|thumb|Ceiling hung mosquito netting.]]\nEvents marking World Malaria Day 2014 in Nigeria included a demonstration of [[anti-malarial bed net]]s, testing and distribution of anti-malarial drugs, seminars on progress in combating and controlling malaria, and the inclusion of African footballers in the campaign to combat malaria.<ref>Federal Ministry of Health. [http://www.nmcp.gov.ng/World-Malaria-Day-2014 Are You Ready for World Malaria Day 2014?] Abuja, 11 April 2014. Accessed 7 October 2014.</ref>\n\nAs of 2016, the Federal Ministry of Health has pledged to end Malaria.<ref>[http://www.nmcp.gov.ng/ \"Home\"]</ref> The U.S. Ambassador to Nigeria, James F. Entwistle, has pledged continued support and noted the possibility of ending Malaria in Nigeria.<ref>[https://nigeria.usembassy.gov/oped_04252016.html \"Opinion Editorial\"]</ref>\n\n===United States===\n[[Image:George W. Bush delivers remarks on Malaria Awareness Day 2007.jpg|thumb|President Bush addresses Americans in The White House Rose Garden about the issues of malaria]]\nApril 25 was designated as ''Malaria Awareness Day'' in 2007 by President [[George W. Bush]], who called on Americans to join in on the goal to eradicate malaria on the African continent.<ref name=\"GB\">George W. Bush. The White House: Office of the Press Secretary. [https://georgewbush-whitehouse.archives.gov/news/releases/2007/04/20070424-11.html Malaria Awareness Day, 2007.] 24 April 2007.</ref>  President Bush described it as a day when \"we focus our attention on all who suffer from this terrible disease -- especially the millions on the continent of Africa. We remember the millions more who died from this entirely preventable and treatable disease.\"  President Bush shared the White House's strategic plan against malaria, which included endeavors to distribute bed nets with the New York-based nonprofit group [[Malaria No More]].<ref name=\"WH\">The White House: Office of the Press Secretary. [https://georgewbush-whitehouse.archives.gov/news/releases/2007/04/20070425-2.html President Bush and Mrs. Bush Discuss Malaria Awareness Day.] 25 April 2007.</ref>\n\nOther former U.S. Presidents are involved in anti-malaria efforts. Former President [[Bill Clinton]]'s [[Clinton Foundation]] includes an anti-malaria component that, according to director [[Inder Singh (philanthropist)|Inder Singh]] has distributed anti-malaria drugs to millions in Africa and Asia.<ref name=\"MIT\">[http://hst.mit.edu/servlet/ControllerServlet?handler=PublicHandler&action=browse&pageId=2261 BEP grad Inder Singh orchestrates affordable malaria drug development], Harvard-MIT Health Sciences.</ref>\n\nMany prominent companies, organizations, and celebrities have declared initiatives to join the fight against malaria to mark this day. These include a $3 million \"challenge grant\" announced by [[ExxonMobil]] to match donations dollar by dollar to [[Malaria No More]], as part of the \"[[Idol Gives Back]]\" episodes of [[American Idol]], which was aired on Malaria Awareness Day.  [[Major League Soccer]] Commissioner [[Don Garber]] also announced that the league would promote malaria awareness and bed net fundraising promotions in the month of April leading up to  Malaria Awareness Day. Actress [[Ashley Judd]], announced the April launch of a new initiative called \u201c5 & Alive,\u201d which will focus on the devastating effects of malaria on children under 5.  The [[Boys & Girls Clubs of America]] announced their own national campaign called \"Malaria Prevention: Deadly Disease.  Simple Solution\", which will partner with Malaria No More to approach all 4.7 Million Club members worldwide to ask for $10 bed net donations.<ref name=\"MNM\">Malaria No More. [https://web.archive.org/web/20070928013156/http://www.malarianomore.org/media/malarianomore-mad-32907.pdf Run up to April 25, the First Malaria Awareness Day in the US.] 29 March 2007.</ref>\n\nThe movement is not without its critics, such as the African economist [[Dambisa Moyo]] who warns that the short term benefits of aid such as mosquito nets can have long term detrimental effects to the sustainability of African economies. When the markets are flooded with foreign nets then this puts African entrepreneurs out of business.{{citation needed|date=October 2014}}\n\n==See also==\n*[https://www.festivaldayes.com/2020/04/24/%e0%a4%b5%e0%a4%b0%e0%a5%8d%e0%a4%b2%e0%a5%8d%e0%a4%a1-%e0%a4%ae%e0%a4%b2%e0%a5%87%e0%a4%b0%e0%a4%bf%e0%a4%af%e0%a4%be-%e0%a4%a6%e0%a4%bf%e0%a4%b5%e0%a4%b8/ World Malaria 